'''Yata ni Imasu Kushitamahiko Shrine''' (やたにいますくしたまひこじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in {{ill|lt=Yata Village (Nara Prefecture)|Q17173675|WD=Q17173675|lt=Yata-chō|1=Yata}}, {{ill|lt=Yamatokōriyama|Q118213|WD=Q118213|1=Yamatokōriyama}}, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} listed as a large shrine, and its former {{ill|lt=shrine rank|Q10444029|WD=Q10444029|1=Shakaku}} was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}}. It is also known as Yaochi Shrine or Yaochi Myōjin<ref name="観光ナビ">[http://yamatokoriyama.locodoco.net/sightseeing/sightseeing-cate03/402.html#firstPage Loco-Doko Tourism Navi: Yata ni Imasu Kushitamahiko Shrine]</ref>.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* Principal deities - Kushitamahiko-no-Kami ({{ill|lt=Nigihayahi|Q10949054|WD=Q10949054|lt=Kushitama-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|1=Nigihayahi}}), {{ill|lt=Mikashikiyahime|Q11341880|WD=Q11341880|lt=Mikashikiyahime-no-Mikoto|1=Mikashikiya-hime}}

=== History ===
The exact date of the shrine's founding is unknown. According to the '{{ill|lt=Sendai Kuji Hongi|Q2716751|WD=Q2716751|1=Kujiki}},' the enshrined deity {{ill|lt=Nigihayahi|Q10949054|WD=Q10949054|lt=Kushitama-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|1=Nigihayahi}} flew through the sky riding the {{ill|lt=Ama-no-Iwafune|Q126914107|WD=Q126914107|1=Ama-no-iwafune}} (Heavenly Rock Ship). It is said that the second arrow that Kushitama-Nigihayahi-no-Kami shot from heaven landed at the spot where this shrine was built<ref name="観光ナビ"/>. Furthermore, the area came to be called "Yata" (arrow-field) because of this event.

In the entry for divine estate grants of various shrines dated {{ill|lt=Daidō (Japan)|Q1373191|WD=Q1373191|lt=Daidō|1=Daidō}} 1 ({{ill|lt=806|Q30021|WD=Q30021|1=806}}) in the '{{ill|lt=Shinchō Kakushikifushō|Q11502312|WD=Q11502312|1=Shinshō Kyakuchokufushō}},' it states "Yata Shrine, two households, {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|lt=Yamato|1=Yamato Province}}," confirming that the shrine is an ancient institution predating that record<ref>Nara Prefecture History reference</ref>. Additionally, {{ill|lt=Emperor Nintoku|Q313119|WD=Q313119|1=Emperor Nintoku}}'s consort {{ill|lt=Yata no Himemiko|Q10892311|WD=Q10892311|lt=Princess Yata|1=Princess Yata}} is thought to have come from this area<ref>From 'Shikinaisha no Kenkyū,' Volume 2</ref>.

The shrine is regarded as the greatest ancient shrine of the region; from its founding through the first half of the 6th century, it is said to have prospered as the foremost celebrated shrine in the entire {{ill|lt=Kinai|Q906708|WD=Q906708|1=Kinai}} region<ref name="観光ナビ"/>. It is the head shrine among the ten shrines of {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}} {{ill|lt=Soejimo District|Q11560415|WD=Q11560415|1=Soejimo district}} listed in the '{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyōchō|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}},' and is an {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}.

In the Shrine Registry of {{ill|lt=1879|Q7783|WD=Q7783|1=1879}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 12), the shrine's deity was listed as {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q11059539|lt=Ame-no-Futodama-no-Mikoto|1=Futodama}}. It appears that the {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Meiji government|1=UNKNOWN}} applied pressure to have Ame-no-Futodama-no-Mikoto enshrined for approximately 40 years.

In the Meiji era, the shrine was ranked as a gōsha, but in October of {{ill|lt=1938|Q18645|WD=Q18645|1=1938}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 13), it was elevated to {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=kensha|1=Ken-sha|WD=Q90139226}}.

Because of the tradition that Kushitama-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto flew through the sky on the Ama-no-Iwafune, Kushitama-Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto is revered as the ancestral deity of aviation, and an Aviation Festival is held every year on September 20<ref name="観光案内">[https://www.yk-kankou.jp/spotDetail24.html Yamatokōriyama City Tourism Association: Yata ni Imasu Kushitamahiko Shrine]</ref>. In the upper story of the gate tower, a {{ill|lt=propeller|Q922654|WD=Q922654|1=Propeller (aeronautics)}} said to have been used on a {{ill|lt=fighter aircraft|Q127771|WD=Q127771|1=Fighter aircraft}} has been dedicated and placed on display<ref name="観光ナビ"/>.

Within the precinct there is a Ni-no-ya-zuka (Second Arrow Mound)<ref name="観光ナビ"/>. There is also a theory that this very area is the site of {{ill|lt=Yamatai|Q844295|WD=Q844295|1=Yamatai}}<ref name="観光案内"/>.

=== Precinct ===
* Honden ({{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|WD=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}) - Rebuilt in the early {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|WD=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}. One-bay {{ill|lt=kasuga-zukuri|Q3193781|WD=Q3193781|1=Kasuga-zukuri}}, cypress-bark roofing<ref name="文化財">[https://www.city.yamatokoriyama.lg.jp/soshiki/machidukuri_senryaku/rekishi_bunkazai/bunkazai101/j_bunkazai/kenzobutsu/1869.html Yamatokōriyama City Cultural Properties: Yata ni Imasu Kushitamahiko Shrine]</ref>.
* Shinmon (sacred gate)
* Haiden
* Ni-no-ya-zuka (Second Arrow Mound)
* Rōmon (gate tower)
* Shamusho (shrine office)

=== Auxiliary shrines ===
* {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Hachiman Shrine|1=Hachiman shrine|WD=Q11390939}} (Important Cultural Property) - Deity: {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Homudawake-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}. Rebuilt in the mid-Muromachi period<ref name="文化財"/>.
* {{ill|lt=Wakamiya Shrine|Q11616280|WD=Q11616280|1=Wakamiya Shrine}} - Deities: {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Umashimaji-no-Mikoto|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|1=Amaterasu|WD=Q455602}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Mizuhanome-no-Kami|1=Mizuhanome|WD=Q8191796}}
* Outlying shrines
** Nushito Shrine - Deities: {{ill|lt=Nigihayahi|Q10949054|WD=Q10949054|lt=Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto|1=Nigihayahi}}, {{ill|lt=Mikashikiyahime|Q11341880|WD=Q11341880|lt=Mikashikiyahime-no-Mikoto|1=Mikashikiya-hime}}. Alternatively, one theory holds the deities are Mikashikiyahime-no-Mikoto and {{ill|lt=Ame-no-Hiritome-no-Mikoto|Q85879124|WD=Q85879124|1=Ame no Hiratome}} (あめのひりとめのみこと), but it appears that Ame-no-Hiritome-no-Mikoto was only temporarily enshrined due to Meiji government pressure. Being both an outlying shrine and an {{ill|lt=otabisho|Q11489117|WD=Q11489117|1=Otabisho}} (sacred resting place for the portable shrine), considering its role as otabisho, the deities appear to be the two kami Nigihayahi-no-Mikoto and Mikashikiyahime-no-Mikoto<ref>Confirmed with the chief priest</ref>.
** {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yasaka Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}: Deity: {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Susanoo|1=UNKNOWN}}. Currently independent.

